        <span class="section-number">01 — About</span>
        <span class="tag tag--rust">Project Overview</span>
        <h2>A Plaza That Works<br>For Its Community</h2>
        <p>
          This project examines Montefiore Square — a triangular pedestrian plaza at the 
          intersection of Broadway, St. Nicholas Avenue, and 179th Street in Washington Heights / 
          Harlem — and proposes a comprehensive redesign centered on community commerce, 
          cultural activation, and public life.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="about-grid">
        <div class="about-text fade-up">
          <h3>Project Goal</h3>
          <p>
            To transform Montefiore Square from a low-activity, hard-surface remnant space 
            into a thriving community market plaza that reflects the cultural identity of 
            its surrounding neighborhood, supports local vendors, and provides year-round 
            programming for residents of all ages.
          </p>
          <p>
            The essential question guiding this work is: <strong>How can a small urban plaza 
            become an economic and social anchor for a Harlem community that has historically 
            lacked formal public market space?</strong>
          </p>
          <p>
            Using AI-assisted image generation as an ideation tool, this project explores 
            multiple redesign directions before arriving at a final proposal that balances 
            market programming, landscape, circulation, and community identity.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="fade-up" style="transition-delay: 0.15s;">
          <div class="info-card">
            <h4>Project Track Info</h4>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Focus:</strong> Community Market &amp; Business Activity</li>
              <li><strong>Site:</strong> Montefiore Square / Montefiore Park, Harlem, NYC</li>
              <li><strong>Tools used:</strong> DALL·E (ChatGPT), Google Maps, NYC DOT references</li>
              <li><strong>Key users:</strong> Local residents, street vendors, families, commuters</li>
              <li><strong>Design goal:</strong> Vendor kiosks, weekend market, public art, shade</li>
              <li><strong>Reference:</strong> NYC DOT Street Design Manual</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

